@Node "Description" "What it does..."

	****** Description

	Dlxrename  is  a small cli utility for those users that need to do
changes in a lot of files at same time and no not want to spend his time
and his patience in this stupid work.

Example:  imagine a subdir full of files such as:

	sarah_23.jpg
	sarah1.jpg
	s-12_anna&sarah.GIF
	13_sarah.JPG
	Sarah_miller_12.iff
	....
	...
	..
	etc!

	With DlxRename you can to this in one step!

	Sarah_miller_001.jpg
	Sarah_miller_002.jpg
	Sarah_miller_003.gif
	Sarah_miller_004.jpg
	Sarah_miller_005.iff
	....
	...
	..
	etc!

	Imagine renaming 1000 files of pictures!!!!  an inferno!, but using
DlxRename, the heaven makes it for you!

@EndNode

@Node "Usage" "The real thing!"

	****** Usage

	The usage is quite simply there is three categories

	@{" Do serial renaming " link "serial"}
	@{" Do change renaming " link "changes"}
	@{" Do anim renaming   " link "anims"}


	Remember  if  you  are badly remembering the parameter list you can
        type "dlxrename ?" for help

@EndNode

@node "serial" "Renaming into series"


	****** Commands to do serial renaming
	 
	-z 	sets the number of zeros to add to the serial number.
		this can be a value from 0 to 5
 
	-s	sets the starting number, this can be a value from 0 to
                above.

	-o	No sort, by default DlxRename sorts alphabetically the
                files before do the rename operation, if you specify this
		the program don't sort the files.


	To do serial renaming is obligatory to specify a name.
	

	There is some examples of serial renaming:

	sarah_23.jpg
	sarah1.jpg
	s-12_anna&sarah.GIF
	13_sarah.JPG
	Sarah_miller_12.iff
	....
	...
	..
	etc!

	Type: "DlxRename Sarah" and you obtain this:

	Sarah_001.jpg
	Sarah_002.jpg
	Sarah_003.gif
	Sarah_004.jpg
	Sarah_005.iff
	....
	...
	..
	etc!

	Dlxrename always maintains the original extension from the source
        archive,  but  If  you  specify an extension like this:
        "DlxRename Sarah.jpg", you can change all extensions.
	obtain:

	Sarah_001.jpg
	Sarah_002.jpg
	Sarah_003.jpg
	Sarah_004.jpg
	Sarah_005.jpg
	....
	...
	..
	etc!

	You can specify the number for starting naming type this
	"DlxRename Sarah -s8", and you obtain:

	Sarah_008.jpg
	Sarah_009.jpg
	Sarah_010.gif
	Sarah_011.jpg
	Sarah_012.iff
	....
	...
	..
	etc!

	If you want to specify the number of zeros for the index type this
	"DlxRename Sarah -z5", and you obtain:

	Sarah_00001.jpg
	Sarah_00002.jpg
	Sarah_00003.gif
	Sarah_00004.jpg
	Sarah_00005.iff
	....
	...
	..
	etc!
	
	The maximum number for the zero option is 5 and the minimum is 0 if
        you specify 0 no zeros will be added to the numeration. like this

	Sarah_1.jpg
	Sarah_2.jpg
	Sarah_3.gif
	Sarah_4.jpg
	Sarah_5.iff

	You can also specify the two options at once like this:
        "Dlxrename Sarah -s3 -z4"

	Sarah_0003.jpg
	Sarah_0004.jpg
	Sarah_0005.gif
	Sarah_0006.jpg
	Sarah_0007.iff
	
	Since  version  1.0  DlxRename  by  default  sorts the archive list
	before  rename,  but  if you didn't want to do this you can use the
	option -o (No sort) like as:

	"Dlxrename Sarah -s3 -z4 -o"

@endnode

@node "changes" "Renaming doing changes in existing file names"

	****** Commands to do changes in names

	-x  = Extension, allows to you to add an extension to your name
              files.
	-r  = Remove extension, removes any extension from your name files.

        -c  = Change case, allows to you to change the case.

	-u  = Space substitution, allows to you to replace spaces by another
              character that you wish.

	String replacement.

	-t1 = old string

	-t2 = new string

	These  parameters  works  without suply any name to the program, if
	you  specify  any of these paremeters giving a name to the program,
        you don't obtain any effect.  If you do anything like this:

	"DlxRename -xjpg -ca Mouse"

	The program works in the serial form...

	Mouse_001
	Mouse_002
	Mouse_003.jpg
        Mouse.004.pcx
	....
	...
	..
	.

	The options works as..
	
	"DlxRename -xjpg"

	If you have a lot of files like this:

	sarah_23
	sarah1
	s-12_anna&sarah
	13_sarah
	Sarah_miller_12

	you obtain:

	sarah_23.jpg
	sarah1.jpg
	s-12_anna&sarah.jpg
	13_sarah.jpg
	Sarah_miller_12.jpg

	If you have files with already have an extension you can do a
        little disaster like this:

	sarah_23.jpg.jpg
	sarah1.iff.jpg
	s-12_anna&sarah.pcx.jpg
	13_sarah.info.jpg
	Sarah_miller_12.iff.jpg

	In this case if you want to substitute an extension by another you
        need to use the -r (Remove extension) and the -x (add extension) at
        same time like this:

	"DlxRename -xjpg -r"

	If You have:

	sarah_23.jpg
	sarah1.iff
	s-12_anna&sarah.pcx
	13_sarah.info
	Sarah_miller_12.iff

	You obtain:

	sarah_23.jpg
	sarah1.jpg
	s-12_anna&sarah.jpg
	13_sarah.jpg
	Sarah_miller_12.jpg

	When  typing  file names from CLI, sometimes spaces are a hell, you
	type  the  name one time and another and the program that are using
	tells  you  "i  cant  find  the  file  xxxx", the reason?  the name
	contains spaces and you need to type the name quoted.

	So  if you don't like spaces in file names the parameter -u is made
	for you.

	Supose you have the files:

	Some stupid mices
	Sarah Miller.jpg
	My super file!
        ram disk.info

	if you type:

	"DlxRename -u"

	you obtain:

	Somestupidmices
	SarahMiller.jpg
	Mysuperfile!
        ramdisk.info

	But supose that you didn't want to kill the spaces, you can do
        something like this:

	"DlxRename -u_"

	And you obtain:
	
	Some_stupid_mices
	Sarah_Miller.jpg
	My_super_file!
        ram_disk.info

	Or supose that you like $!!!

	"DlxRename -u$"
	
	And you obtain:

	Some$stupid$mices
	Sarah$Miller.jpg
	My$super$file!
        ram$disk.info	

	Simple and nice :)

	Supose  that you want all of your files in Upper case, in this case
	we need to use the -c option (change case).

	There are three variants in this parameter:

	a) All Letters to lower case
	b) All Letters to upper case
	c) only the first letter of each word in Uppercase
	
	If you want to use the option a, you need to type:

	"DlxRename -ca"

	And you obtain:

	some$stupid$mices
	sarah$miller.jpg
	my$super$file!
        ram$disk.info

	If you want to use the option 'b' or the 'c', do same as 'a' option:

	"DlxRename -cb" or "DlxRename -cc"

	this is the last example, all the options at same time!

	if you have:

	SOME STUPID MICES
	Sarah_Miller.jpg
	My Super File!.jpg
        ram disk.info

	And you do:

	"DlxRename -xpicture -cc -r -u-"

	You obtain:
	
	Some-Stupid-Mices.picture
	Sarah_Miller.picture
	My-Super-File!.picture
        Ram-Disk.picture

	Text replace is simple as the abobe options, supose that you want
        to change all 'calc's on the following archive list:

	1st_calc.txt
	calc.point.txt
	calculated_incoming.ssc

	you simply do:

	dlxrename -t1calc -t2Mouse

	you obtain:

	1st_Mouse.txt
	Mouse.point.txt
	Mouseulated_incoming.ssc

	but if you want to kill all the mices use '/' in the -t2 parameter
        like this:

	dlxrename -t1Mouse -t2/

	and you obtain:

	1st_.txt
	.point.txt
	ulated_incoming.ssc

	@{b}Note:@{ub}
	The  replacement  options  works as case sensitive and don't acceps
	spaces.

@endnode

@node "anims" "Renaming Animations!"

	****** Commands to do Anim's renaming

	-N   = Maintains the actual format of the anim
              
	-NDR = Convert Deluxe paint index to real3d index

	-NRD = Convert real3d index to Deluxe paint index

	-B   = number of frame to begin the rename.

	-E   = number of frame to stop the rename

	-S   = number to start renaming.


	Sounds a little strange, but the thing works like this:

	supose that you have a lot of frames from the program Real3D
	and you want to use them in Dpaint, Dpaints need the index in the
        form: name_00000 and real3d use name0, renaming all of the frames
        is a tedious work... but now you have DlxRename!!!!

	Imagine you have:

	myanim0
	myanim1
	myanim2
	myanim3
	myanim4
	....
	...
	..
	.
	myanim1000
	....
	...
	..
	.
	etc!
	
	If you want to rename them to the Dpaint's format symply do

	DlxRename myanim -nrd

	and you get:

	myanim00000
	myanim00001
	myanim00002
	myanim00003
	myanim00004
	....
	...
	..
	.
	myanim01000
	....
	...
	..
	.
	etc!

	Note that Dlxrename assumes by default 0 as the starting frame
        you need to specify the starting number if it's diferent of 0!!!

	like as: DlxRename myanim -nrd -b5

	Maybe you want to do the inverse operation convert a deluxe paint
        anim to the real3d format, you need to use:

	DlxRename myanim -ndr -b1

	By now DlxRename assumes that you want to rename the frames by the
        first to the end, but maybe you want to rename only the 4 first
        frames.

	You do:

	DlxRename myanim -nrd -b0 -e3

	and obtain:

	myanim00000
	myanim00001
	myanim00002
	myanim00003
	myanim4
	....
	...
	..
	.
	myanim1000
	....
	...
	..
	.
	etc!

	But supose that you want to change the numbers in the anim without
        changing its format you can do this:

	dlxrename myanim -n -b0 -e3 -s20

	myanim20
	myanim21
	myanim22
	myanim23
	myanim4
	....
	...
	..
	.
	myanim1000
	....
	...
	..
	.
	etc!

	It's  easy!   to  do  anim  renames!   only specify the format, the
	starting  frame,  the  ending  frame  and  if you want the starting
	number to do the index!

@endnode

@Node "History" "Program History"

	****** Program History

	V0.5 - First Public release

	V0.6 - Second Public release
	     - Fixed an alien bug caused by a buggie blitz library
	     - Added extension recognition
